"# Chapter 4 — Lisp — the S-expression tradition

Motoi Scheme is a Lisp. So is Common Lisp, Scheme, Racket, Clojure,
Emacs Lisp, and dozens of others. The word 'Lisp' names both the
original 1958 language and the whole family that descends from it.

This chapter is about that family, in more detail than Chapter 3 of
Book of Language Ancestors (which was about McCarthy the person).

## McCarthy's 1958 Lisp

The original Lisp was designed at MIT in 1958 and first implemented
in 1958-1959 by McCarthy's grad student Steve Russell. It was aimed
at symbolic computation — programs that manipulate symbols rather
than crunch numbers.

The design ideas from McCarthy:
- Everything is a list built from atoms and pairs.
- Programs are lists.
- Program evaluation is walking a list.
- Functions can call themselves (recursion).
- Memory is managed automatically (garbage collection).

The syntax was intended as a temporary hack. McCarthy planned to
design a more traditional-looking syntax on top, called M-expressions,
but the S-expression version (nested parentheses) turned out to be
so convenient that nobody built the M-expressions in a hurry.
Sixty-seven years later, we still write Lisp in S-expressions.

The metacircular evaluator — a Lisp interpreter written in Lisp,
about half a page long — appeared in McCarthy's 1960 paper. It
remains one of the elegant demonstrations in computer science.

## The Lisp family branches

Through the 1960s and 1970s, Lisp splintered into many dialects.
Each institution running Lisp on a big computer had its own
variant. Some notable branches:

- **LISP 1.5** (MIT, 1962) — an early clean version McCarthy's team
  documented. The reference Lisp.

- **Maclisp** (MIT AI Lab, late 1960s to 1980s) — used on the PDP-10.
  Fast, extensible. Ran a lot of famous AI programs (Macsyma, Zork,
  SHRDLU).

- **Interlisp** (BBN and Xerox PARC, 1966 onwards) — a Lisp with an
  integrated programming environment (early ideas of an IDE). Ran on
  Xerox workstations.

- **Franz Lisp** (Berkeley, 1970s) — Maclisp on Unix. Named after
  Franz Liszt.

- **Zetalisp** (MIT AI Lab, 1978) — the Lisp of the Lisp Machines.

- **Emacs Lisp** (1985) — the Lisp that emacs is written in and
  extended in.

By the early 1980s, this fragmentation was a problem. Programs
written in one Lisp didn't run on another. A standardization effort
began.

## Common Lisp

Common Lisp was standardized in 1984 with the book *Common Lisp:
the Language* (CLtL) by Guy Steele, and standardized formally as
ANSI Common Lisp in 1994. The goal was to unify the various
industrial Lisp dialects — Maclisp, Zetalisp, Franz Lisp, and
others — into one that everyone could target.

Common Lisp is large. The specification is around a thousand pages.
It includes:
- All the classic Lisp features: lists, symbols, closures, macros.
- Object orientation (CLOS, the Common Lisp Object System).
- Powerful metaprogramming (define your own control constructs).
- Multiple dispatch for methods.
- Restarts and conditions (rich error handling).
- A standard library covering strings, hash tables, I/O, arrays,
  streams, format strings, etc.

Common Lisp is the industrial Lisp. It's what you use if you want
a Lisp with everything included. It has been used to build symbolic
math systems, airline reservation engines, expert systems, and much
else. It's still in active use, though not fashionable.

## Scheme

Scheme (McCarthy would say a dialect of Lisp; the Scheme community
would say a distinct language) was designed by Sussman and Steele
at MIT in 1975. It stayed small on purpose. Chapter 4 and Chapter 5
of Book of Language Ancestors cover the designers.

Scheme is minimal by comparison to Common Lisp:
- Small core (a few dozen special forms and primitive procedures).
- Guaranteed proper tail calls.
- First-class continuations (call/cc).
- Lexical scoping (Scheme was the first big Lisp to insist).
- Hygienic macros (syntactic extensions that don't accidentally
  capture variables).

Motoi Scheme is in this Scheme tradition — small kernel, lexical
scope, first-class functions, macros as a first-class extension
mechanism.

## Clojure

Clojure is a modern Lisp designed by Rich Hickey, first released
2007. It runs on the JVM (with variants for JavaScript and .NET).

Clojure's design choices:
- Persistent immutable data structures by default. If you want to
  mutate, you have to be explicit.
- STM (software transactional memory) and other principled models
  for shared state.
- Macros, closures, and other classic Lisp features.
- Interoperability with the host platform (Java classes, JavaScript
  objects, etc.).

Clojure is aimed at practical software engineering with a functional
bent. It has a substantial following in industry, especially at
companies where the JVM matters but Java's verbosity chafes.

## Racket

Racket (formerly PLT Scheme) is a Scheme descendant designed as a
research vehicle for programming-language design. Started at Rice
University in 1994, later moving to Northwestern and Utah. Its main
focus is on being a platform for creating new languages — you can
build your own DSLs on top of Racket relatively easily.

Racket is also the language of the textbook *How to Design Programs*
(HtDP), which teaches introductory programming. HtDP is used in
many universities.

## What makes a Lisp a Lisp

The uniting feature of every Lisp is the S-expression. Programs
and data have the same shape — nested lists. This means:

- Programs can be manipulated as data (metaprogramming).
- Macros can extend the language.
- Interpreters and compilers for Lisp are small compared to other
  languages.
- The syntax is uniform; no operator precedence to memorize.

The downsides:
- The parentheses take getting used to.
- Some programmers find the density visually noisy.
- The uniformity means less visual distinction between different
  kinds of syntax, which some people miss.

## A tiny example

The metacircular evaluator, in essence, in Motoi Scheme:

```
(define (my-eval expr env)
  (cond
    ((number? expr) expr)
    ((symbol? expr) (env-lookup env expr))
    ((pair? expr)
     (case (car expr)
       ((quote)  (cadr expr))
       ((if)     (if (my-eval (cadr expr) env)
                     (my-eval (caddr expr) env)
                     (my-eval (cadddr expr) env)))
       ((lambda) (list 'closure (cadr expr) (cddr expr) env))
       (else     (my-apply (my-eval (car expr) env)
                           (map (lambda (e) (my-eval e env))
                                (cdr expr))))))))

(define (my-apply fn args)
  (cond
    ((procedure? fn) (apply fn args))
    ((eq? (car fn) 'closure)
     (my-eval-body (caddr fn)
                   (env-extend (cadddr fn) (cadr fn) args)))))
```

That is a Lisp interpreter written in Lisp. Roughly twenty lines.
McCarthy's original 1960 metacircular evaluator was about the same
size. This is the elegance Lisp keeps returning to.

## What Motoi wants you to take from this

Lisp is not one language. It's a family with a shared shape and many
distinct members. Each member specializes for a niche: Common Lisp
for industrial power, Scheme for pedagogical minimalism, Clojure for
JVM-based functional work, Racket for language-building.

Motoi Scheme belongs to the Scheme branch. Small. Uniform. Meant to
teach. The book you're reading now is written in the same shape as
the programs Motoi runs — S-expressions annotated with prose. Same
idea McCarthy had in 1958.")
